<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/technology <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/technology" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 10 日星期四 23:44:57 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[A New Omicron Subvariant, Dubbed ‘Eris,’ Heralds Covid-19’s Resurgence]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>我们对美国最常见的亚变体 EG.5 的了解<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124938"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833284?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">曼哈顿的一个弹出式 Covid-19 测试帐篷。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的加比·琼斯</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124938"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/brianna-abbott" itemprop="url" rel="author">布莱恩娜·阿博特</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jon-kamp" itemprop="url" rel="author">乔恩·坎普</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-s-hopkins" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·S·霍普金斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日下午 3:18（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>现在还不要指望 Covid-19 被排除在外。</p><p>随着 Omicron 变种的另一个分支势头强劲，美国的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-rates-rising-summer-780ab1d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Covid-19 感染人数</a>正在上升——在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rsv-influenza-covid-19-tripledemic-this-winter-11667560508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">呼吸道疾病</a>通常会激增的秋季之前。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-do-we-actually-know-about-covid-19-not-enough-ec1dcafe?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">该病毒的持续进化</a>提醒人们，尽管这种疾病的破坏性远不如以前，但 Covid-19 仍然对许多人来说是一个麻烦，对一些人来说仍然是一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/long-covid-symptoms-recovery-not-over-2e535790?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">严重的风险</a>。废水中病毒浓度的不断上升和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/face-mask-mandates-fall-away-among-many-hospitals-doctors-6ecaa3e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">医院感染的</a>增加表明，Covid-19 仍然难以预测。</p><p>这种名为 EG.5 的新亚变体是另一个名为 XBB.1.9.2 的变体的后代，据世界卫生组织称，自 8 月 7 日以来，至少有 51 个国家报告了该变体，该组织将 EG.5 归类为本周感兴趣的一个变体。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833823?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> X（以前称为 Twitter）上的一些科学家将其非正式地称为“Eris”。世界卫生组织表示，与其他 Omicron 亚变体一样，EG.5 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/omicrons-trajectory-shows-challenge-of-maintaining-immune-defenses-11651829400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">具有免疫逃逸特性</a>，但没有迹象表明它更严重。</p><p>据美国疾病控制与预防中心称，截至 8 月 5 日，EG.5 预计约占美国病例的 17%，使其成为美国最流行的病毒版本。它是由十多个 Omicron 分支组成的动物园之一，估计至少占病例的 1%。</p><p>路易斯安那州卫生官员兼路易斯安那州卫生部医疗主任约瑟夫·坎特博士表示，由于没有足够的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cdc-director-rochelle-walensky-politicization-science-9c291c7e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">检测和测序数据</a>，疾病预防控制中心无法再对美国每个地区进行变异预测。</p><p> “我们预计 EG.5 将继续发挥重要作用，”坎特说。</p><p>卫生官员、疫苗制造商和医生正在为秋季疫苗接种活动做准备，这次活动将与之前的活动有所不同：疫苗将通过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-administration-plans-for-end-of-covid-19-shot-treatment-coverage-11660838418?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">商业市场</a>而不是政府购买分发给药房和医生办公室。这些疫苗针对的是最近占主导地位的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/next-covid-shots-in-the-u-s-will-target-omicron-offshoot-xbb-1-5-35e212a0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">XBB.1.5 菌株，</a>符合美国食品和药物管理局今年早些时候制定的指示。</p><p>坎特说，针对 XBB.1.5 更新的助推器应该保留针对 EG.5 的良好保护，因为 Omicron 子变体是相似的。他说，很难预测这种保护会持续多久。</p><p>辉瑞<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pfizers-covid-boost-crashes-to-earth-51e1d0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">首席执行官艾伯特·布尔拉 (Albert Bourla)</a>本月表示，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PFE" class="company-name">辉瑞</a>预计其新疫苗将于本月获得批准，疫苗接种可能于 9 月开始。辉瑞公司发言人表示，预计该增强剂能够对抗 EG.5，因为它是 Omicron 的一个分支，但正在进行实验室测试以确保这一点。辉瑞和合作伙伴<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BNTX" class="company-name">BioNTech</a>在 6 月份的会议上向 FDA 顾问介绍了如何更新疫苗的动物测试。</p><p> FDA 不太可能要求制造商生产针对 EG.5 的疫苗，因为供应无法及时准备好以供秋季活动使用。辉瑞和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MRNA" class="company-name">Moderna</a>至少需要三个月的时间才能针对 Covid-19 进行 mRNA 注射。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>发言人表示，Moderna 的更新疫苗供应充足，正在等待 FDA 批准分配剂量。他说，初步测试表明该镜头对 EG.5 有效，更多测试正在进行中。</p><p>一位发言人表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVAX" class="">Novavax</a>的 Covid-19 疫苗使用了不同的技术，该公司正在向监管机构提交数据以授权其加强剂，并预计在 9 月份获得许可并发货。</p><p>是否立即接受加强注射或等待新的加强注射<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/think-you-never-got-covid-19-thank-your-genes-d61c7507?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取决于某人的健康状况和风险</a>， <strong>&nbsp;</strong>威尔康奈尔医学院微生物学和免疫学教授约翰摩尔博士说。他说，患有已有疾病或免疫系统受损的人以及未接种疫苗的人仍然面临高风险。</p><p> “如果您和您的医生认为您现在需要加强注射，请立即注射，”摩尔说。 “这非常有个性。没有一个简单的桶可以容纳每个美国人。”</p><p>去年，RSV 早期严重激增以及流感导致<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rsv-hospitalizations-babies-young-children-11668080478?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">儿科医院不堪重负</a>，卫生官员正在为其他呼吸道感染的增加做好准备。 FDA 已<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/next-vaccine-you-should-get-health-advisers-may-recommend-rsv-shots-60849622?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">批准首款</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-pfizer-rsv-vaccine-rolls-out-into-headwinds-of-hesitancy-74c8aece?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于 60 岁及以上成年人的</a>RSV 疫苗以及一种<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fda-approves-first-rsv-drug-to-protect-all-infants-from-virus-52907caf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于保护婴儿的新药</a>。</p><p> “我们正在进入一个我们并不真正知道这些病毒将如何相互作用的季节，”康涅狄格州公共卫生部专员马尼沙·朱萨尼博士说。</p><p>美国不再像以前那样密切跟踪 Covid-19 感染和住院情况。长期以来，感染情况一直难以记录，因为人们不再在向州卫生当局提供数据的设施中接受检测。医院还取消了对所有患者的常规检测。</p><p>几周来，医院内的 Covid-19 病例一直呈上升趋势。 CDC 表示，截至 7 月底的最新一周内，有 9,056 人因 Covid-19 入院，增长了 12.5%。许多患者因其他原因住院，而不是因为感染，但医院的阳性检测可以反映出社区感染流行率的增加。</p><p> Covid-19 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/one-million-deaths-the-hole-the-pandemic-made-in-u-s-society-11643662159?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">每天都会导致新的死亡病例</a>，尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-u-s-covid-19-death-toll-is-still-rising-93b2b12a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">远未达到大流行初期的峰值</a>。最近的死亡证明数据显示，美国平均每天有不到 100 例 Covid-19 死亡病例。 2021 年 1 月，一周内每天死亡人数达到历史最高值约 3,700 人。</p><p>写信给 Brianna Abbott（ <a href="mailto:brianna.abbott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">brianna.abbott@wsj.com</a> ）、Jon Kamp（ <a href="mailto:Jon.Kamp@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jon.Kamp@wsj.com</a> ）和 Jared S. Hopkins（ <a href="mailto:jared.hopkins@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.hopkins@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 19:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260<author><![CDATA[Brianna AbbottJon KampJared S. Hopkins]]></author><category>华尔街日报健康</category><category>药品</category><category>疫苗</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>特殊药物/药物</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>免疫接种</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>疫情/流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>医疗/程序</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>免疫接种</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>爆发</category><category>流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>医疗</category><category>程序</category><category>药品</category><category>疫苗</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>专门药物</category><category>药物</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[AI Is Generating Security Risks Faster Than Companies Can Keep Up]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>基于人工智能的生成软件的快速增长正在挑战商业技术领导者控制潜在的网络安全问题<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124950"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-228438?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">生成式人工智能使技术供应商和公司更难确定其代码中的内容并使其数字供应链保持最新状态。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Philippe Huguen/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124950"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/belle-lin" itemprop="url" rel="author">林贝儿</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 10 日下午<span class="divider">2:28</span><span class="wsjpro-label">华尔街日报专业版</span></time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-is-generating-security-risks-faster-than-companies-can-keep-up-a2bdedd4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>基于生成人工智能的工具将为员工带来巨大的生产力提升，但负责实施这些工具的商业技术领导者正在努力了解其潜在的网络安全风险。</p><p>随着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="">微软</a><span class="company-name-type">Copilot</span> （一种嵌入公司工作场所软件中的生成人工智能工具）等服务变得越来越普遍，企业领导者现在有责任了解他们所获得的新功能的内部内容，以及它们是否通过了安全要求。</p><p>为了帮助供应链管理，公司长期以来一直依赖从制造商那里收到的货物库存，其中详细说明了每个组件的来源。最近，软件供应商面临着设计类似<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/push-to-explain-what-software-contains-gains-steam-after-log4j-flaw-11643020203?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“软件物料清单”的</a>压力，其中列出了软件代码的内部内容，包括其开源和专有组件。</p><p>如此彻底的清单背后的想法是，公司可以更好地跟踪其软件的具体细节（包括它是否存在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-is-the-log4j-vulnerability-11639446180?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Log4j 软件缺陷</a>等安全漏洞），并更快地对其做出响应。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>网络监控公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SWI" class="">SolarWinds</a>的受污染软件<span class="company-name-type">导致</span>2020 年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/agencies-hacked-in-foreign-cyber-espionage-campaign-11607897866?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">企业和美国政府遭受大规模黑客攻击</a>，迫使许多公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/solarwinds-hack-forces-reckoning-with-supply-chain-security-11610620200" target="_blank" class="icon none">重新评估与第三方软件供应商的关系</a>。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ACN" class="">埃森哲</a>咨询公司网络弹性服务董事总经理罗伯特·博伊斯表示，现在，随着人工智能模型根据公司数据进行训练，企业需要更加了解这些数据可能会在供应链中的哪些地方暴露<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p>生成式人工智能面临的挑战是，该技术发展如此之快，以至于各公司都急于弄清楚它是否会带来新的网络安全挑战或放大现有的安全弱点。与此同时， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companies-are-drowning-in-too-much-ai-1c27c003?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">技术供应商向企业提供了大量</a>基于人工智能的新生成功能和产品，但并非所有这些都是他们需要的，甚至还没有付费。</p><p>分析师表示，这使得人工智能物料清单更加难以管理。他们补充说，大型语言模型非常复杂，几乎不可能对其进行深入审核。</p><p> “大多数安全领导者担心的是其中一些功能缺乏可见性、监控或可解释性，” <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FORR" class="">Forrester Research</a>的网络安全分析师 Jeff Pollard 表示<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p></p><p>欧盟执法机构欧洲刑警组织的数据科学家大卫·约翰逊最近在布鲁塞尔举行的一次会议上表示，在某些情况下，生成式人工智能可能会带来安全风险，因为模型是用预先存在的代码进行训练的。 “该代码可能包含漏洞，因此如果模型随后生成新代码，它可以继承相同的漏洞，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833486?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Daryan “D” Dehghanpisheh，初创公司 Protect AI 的联合创始人兼总裁。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：保护人工智能</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>对生成式人工智能的兴趣为像 Protect AI 这样的初创公司创造了机会，该公司旨在帮助企业通过一个被称为“机器学习物料清单”的平台来跟踪其本土人工智能系统的组件。该公司表示，其平台还可以识别安全政策违规行为和恶意代码注入攻击。</p><p> Protect AI 联合创始人兼总裁 Daryan 表示，这家总部位于西雅图的初创公司最近在流行的开源机器学习工具 MLflow 中发现了一个漏洞，该漏洞可能允许攻击者接管公司的云帐户凭据并访问培训数据。 D”Dehghanpisheh。</p><p>这些类型的攻击<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-ai-hackers-can-simply-talk-computers-into-misbehaving-ad488686?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，加上“提示注入”等新形式，</a>即黑客使用“提示”或基于文本的指令来操纵生成人工智能系统以共享敏感信息，所有这些都代表了首席信息官需要考虑的基于人工智能的供应链风险，德甘皮什说道。</p><p> Protect AI 联合创始人兼首席执行官 Ian Swanson 表示，尽管生成式 AI 的快速增长催生了大量新工具和 AI 模型，但大多数公司仍在努力全面了解其数据、代码和 AI 运营。</p><p>与此同时，一些技术领导者，例如总部位于旧金山的销售和营销软件公司 6sense 的首席信息官 Bryan Wise，在签署新的生成式 AI 功能之前，一直专注于向供应商提出更棘手的问题。</p><p> “如果有人要求生成人工智能产品，”怀斯说，“我们必须更加努力地说，‘告诉我这些数据是如何使用的？您如何确保我们的数据不会被用来改进您的模型？” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833549?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bryan Wise，销售和营销软件公司 6sense 的首席信息官。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：6sense</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>分析师表示，大多数首席信息官都优先考虑<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/generative-ai-pilots-have-companies-reaching-for-the-guardrails-4326704c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">防止公司数据泄露</a>到其领域之外或成为第三方人工智能模型的训练数据。他表示，对于休斯敦殡葬和墓地服务提供商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSV" class="">Carriage Services</a>的首席信息官 Rob Franch 等人来说<span class="company-name-type">，</span>微软等老牌供应商的保证和保护措施有助于缓解这些担忧。</p><p>尽管如此， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/generative-ai-helping-boost-productivity-of-some-software-developers-731fa5a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">生成式人工智能助手帮助程序员编写的</a>代码中仍然存在一个独立但相关的网络安全问题。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="">亚马逊</a><span class="company-name-type">的</span>CodeWhisperer 和微软旗下的 GitHub Copilot 等工具会建议新的代码片段，并向开发人员提供技术建议。</p><p> Forrester 的 Pollard 表示，通过使用此类工具，工程师可能会生成不准确的代码文档、不遵循安全开发实践的代码，或者泄露超出公司通常共享范围的系统信息。</p><p>发动机和发电机制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CMI" class="">康明斯</a>的首席信息安全官迭戈·苏扎 (Diego Souza) 表示，许多供应商在解释其工作原理时不愿意说其产品中的代码是由人工智能编写的<span class="company-name-type">。</span>苏扎表示，他的安全团队测试产品、确保供应商提供有关潜在安全缺陷的报告并在公司将新软件引入其系统之前提供生命周期更新至关重要。 “最大的挑战是了解代码是否是由人工智能编写的，”他说。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hackers-go-pro-seeking-bounties-for-bugs-11565602203?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">错误赏金平台</a>HackerOne 的首席执行官 Mårten Mickos 等行业高管担心“人工智能代码蔓延”，或者米科斯所说的“嘈杂、平庸、怪异、难以追踪”代码的扩散，当它成为一个网络安全问题时，被转化为软件。网络安全公司 Snyk 首席执行官 Peter McKay 表示，随着开发人员使用人工智能工具更快地构建软件，他们也以更快的速度编写易受攻击的代码。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="438" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-729293?width=700&amp;height=438" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">微软的 GitHub Copilot 程序采用 ChatGPT 制造商 OpenAI 的生成式人工智能构建，可以推荐新的代码片段并向开发人员提供技术建议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：GitHub 公司</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>波拉德表示，虽然围绕软件开发和供应链的网络安全实践并不新鲜，但使用人工智能帮助编写代码加剧了挑战。现在，供应商和公司更难确定其代码中的内容并使其软件物料清单保持最新。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KMX" class="">CarMax</a>首席信息和技术官 Shamim Mohammad<span class="company-name-type">正在</span>利用人工智能来提高效率并改善二手车零售商的客户和员工体验。但他表示，使用生成式人工智能也会“增加恶意代码、版权、知识产权和隐私方面的风险”。</p><p>他表示，CarMax 正在开发一种“治理模型”来指导其对人工智能的使用，该模型可以通过教育和设定指导方针和界限来减轻这些风险。</p><p> 6sense 的 Wise 正在对生成式人工智能进行一系列“小赌注”，而不是一头扎进去，他表示，他的评估过程涉及检查该技术的架构和数据实践，而不仅仅是其承诺的业务成果。</p><p> “所有首席信息官都需要更深入地研究，”怀斯说。 “你需要提出正确的问题，才能对自己所做的决定感到放心。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —<em>凯瑟琳·斯塔普 (Catherine Stupp)</em>对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Belle Lin： <a href="mailto:belle.lin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">belle.lin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 18:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-is-generate-security-risks-faster-than-companies-can-keep-up-a2bdedd4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-is-generate-security-risks-faster-than-companies-can-keep-up-a2bdedd4<author><![CDATA[Belle Lin]]></author><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>软件编程工具/语言</category><category>计算</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>信息技术政策</category><category>供应链</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>隐私问题/信息安全</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>专业版</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-网络</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>车麦斯</category><category>克米克斯</category><category>运输服务</category><category>CSV</category><category>康明斯</category><category>CMI</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>信息技术政策</category><category>供应链</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>隐私问题</category><category>信息安全</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>软件编程工具</category><category>语言</category><category>计算</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Amazon Cuts Dozens of House Brands]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>该公司削减了 30 个服装品牌中除三个以外的所有品牌，例如 Goodthreads 和 Lark &amp; Ro <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001123950"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833156?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">由于销售业绩令人失望和立法者的批评，亚马逊去年开始缩减自有品牌业务。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：帕特里克·T.法伦/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001123950"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dana-mattioli" itemprop="url" rel="author">达纳·马蒂奥利</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日下午 2:11（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-cuts-dozens-of-house-brands-as-it-battles-costs-regulators-3f6ad56d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">亚马逊</a>正在放弃数十个自有品牌，作为大幅减少自有品牌业务的一部分，该公司致力于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-to-meet-with-ftc-officials-ahead-of-expected-antitrust-complaint-fbb0927f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">抵御反垄断审查</a>并提振利润。</p><p>据知情人士透露，这家总部位于西雅图的公司去年决定淘汰旗下 30 个服装品牌中的 27 个，例如 Lark &amp; Ro、Daily Ritual 和 Goodthreads。随着亚马逊出售剩余库存，部分品牌目前仍保留在亚马逊网站上，但完成后，其自有品牌服装部门将只剩下三个品牌：Amazon Essentials、Amazon Collection 和 Amazon Aware。</p><p>一些知情人士表示，亚马逊还正在放弃自有品牌家具品牌，一旦 Rivet 和 Stone &amp; Beam 这些商品的库存耗尽，就会逐步淘汰这些品牌。</p><p>目前尚不清楚其他业务部门被削减的品牌的确切数字，但销售一系列家居用品和科技配件的 Amazon Basics 仍将是该公司的重点。</p><p> “我们始终根据客户的需求做出决策，我们了解到，客户会寻找我们最大的品牌（例如 Amazon Basics 和 Amazon Essentials），以获取高品质、高价格的超值产品，”副总裁 Matt Taddy亚马逊自有品牌部门在给《华尔街日报》的一份声明中表示。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p>他表示，亚马逊希望淘汰“不能引起顾客共鸣”的产品。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D340813E-FD24-4A69-98A6-4EDEFF32F1C7&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Famazon-cuts-dozens-of-house-brands-as-it-battles-costs-regulators-3f6ad56d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 《华尔街日报》详细分析了莉娜·汗选择的战斗。图片插图：沉星培<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>经过多年努力建立自有品牌业务后，亚马逊<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-has-been-slashing-private-label-selection-amid-weak-sales-11657849612?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">去年开始缩减</a>自有品牌业务，原因是销售业绩令人失望，并且受到立法者和其他人的批评，他们表示自有品牌业务可能与该公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-competition-shopify-wayfair-allbirds-antitrust-11608235127?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">销售其他品牌的</a>业务发生冲突。该公司还减少了在特殊展示位置的搜索结果页面上提升其自有品牌产品的力度。</p><p>截至 2020 年，亚马逊自有品牌业务拥有 45 个不同自有品牌的 243,000 种产品。</p><p>联邦贸易委员会<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ftc-prepares-possible-antitrust-suit-against-amazon-11675438256?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一直在调查亚马逊的</a>多项做法，并准备对该公司提起反垄断诉讼。亚马逊的代表定于下周与联邦贸易委员会委员会面，作为联邦贸易委员会下个月撤销诉讼之前通常被称为“最后仪式”的仪式的一部分。</p><p>亚马逊表示，自有品牌仅占该公司零售总额的 1%。据《华尔街日报》报道，鉴于该业务规模相对其所产生的监管问题而言较小，该公司去年曾讨论过，如果联邦贸易委员会继续提起诉讼，该公司将退出该业务，作为对联邦贸易委员会的让步<strong>。</strong>目前尚不清楚亚马逊是否已向监管机构提出退出该业务的建议。</p><p>亚马逊发言人在去年发表文章时表示，该公司并未认真考虑关闭自有品牌业务，并计划继续对其进行投资。</p><p>一些知情人士称，亚马逊目前已将自有品牌总数削减至不到 20 个，并退役了为这些品牌生产的数万种产品。</p><p>被淘汰的品牌不会再订购新产品，一旦库存售完，这些品牌将不复存在。已停产品牌中的畅销商品正在 Amazon Essentials 或其他剩余标签下重新命名。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833228?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Amazon Basics 销售一系列家居用品和科技配件，仍将是该公司的重点业务。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：凯西·克利福德/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这些变化与亚马逊在过去两年中为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-has-launched-a-cost-cutting-review-focused-on-unprofitable-business-units-11668094823" target="_blank" class="icon none">减少无利可图的业务和产品而做出</a>的更广泛的努力是一致的，因为面对大流行后的经济低迷，该公司致力于削减成本。这项努力意味着削减无利可图的领域，例如该公司的非杂货实体店。</p><p>自有品牌举措还解决了对其自有品牌竞争行为的审查，这多年来一直困扰着亚马逊。</p><p> 2020 年，《华尔街日报》详细介绍了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-scooped-up-data-from-its-own-sellers-to-launch-competing-products-11587650015?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">亚马逊员工如何使用其平台上的个别第三方卖家数据</a>来开发与这些卖家竞争的亚马逊品牌产品。亚马逊创始人兼时任首席执行官<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/jeff-bezos">杰夫·贝佐斯</a></p>文章发表后，他被传唤到国会反垄断委员会作证。<p></p><p>亚马逊发言人周三表示：“我们明确反对使用非公开的单一卖家数据来确定要推出哪些自有品牌产品，我们的政策比我们所知道的任何零售商都走得更远。”</p><p>据知情人士透露，在那篇 2020 年的文章之后，亚马逊遏制了多年来的做法，即在其网站上的特殊位置上提高自有品牌的搜索结果，而其他卖家只有通过购买广告才能获得这种优势。近期变动。这一变化导致亚马逊的许多品牌被淹没在搜索结果中，从而使商品更难销售。对于亚马逊来说，仓储所有库存的成本非常高，这使其成为成本削减的目标。</p><p>一些公司指责亚马逊以自有品牌销售山寨产品。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WSM" class="company-name">Williams-Sonoma</a>于 2018 年起诉亚马逊，声称这家科技公司以 Rivet 品牌复制了其 West Elm 品牌外观独特的球形餐椅，并销售与其设计几乎相同的其他产品。</p><p>亚马逊后来从其网站上删除了这些商品并解决了诉讼，威廉姆斯-索诺玛获得了有利的结果。</p><p>写信给达纳·马蒂奥利 (Dana Mattioli)： <a href="mailto:dana.mattioli@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dana.mattioli@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 18:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-cuts-dozens-of-house-brands-as-it-battles-costs-regulators-3f6ad56d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-cuts-dozens-of-house-brands-as-it-battles-costs-regulators-3f6ad56d<author><![CDATA[Dana Mattioli]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>专有的</category><category>衣服</category><category>零售批发</category><category>伊泰林</category><category>服装/纺织品</category><category>消费品</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>零售</category><category>技术</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>营销</category><category>反竞争问题</category><category>品牌推广</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>市场/营销</category><category>白标</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>亚马逊网站</category><category>亚马逊</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>营销</category><category>反竞争问题</category><category>品牌推广</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>市场</category><category>白色标签</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>衣服</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>电子邮寄</category><category>纺织品</category><category>消费品</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Maui Wildfires Leave at Least 36 Dead]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>飓风引发的大火摧毁了历史名镇拉海纳<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124181"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1E4C7220-8609-4F03-A17C-70F3E330A2CD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">官员称，飓风引发的野火席卷夏威夷毛伊岛，已造成至少 36 人死亡。卫星图像显示了热门​​旅游小镇拉海纳的破坏规模。照片：Matthew Thayer/毛伊岛新闻/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124181"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alicia-caldwell" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾丽西亚·A·考德威尔</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jennifer-calfas" itemprop="url" rel="author">詹妮弗·卡尔法斯</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-wright" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·赖特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日下午 1:52（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>夏威夷卡胡卢伊——当局称<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-wildfires-maui-big-island-lahaina-hurricane-dora-evacuations-800bf315?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，席卷毛伊岛、摧毁历史名城拉海纳的野火</a>已造成至少 36 人死亡。</p><p>本周早些时候在夏威夷岛上爆发的三场野火是由数百英里外飓风多拉的风力助长的。野火的原因尚未确定。</p><p>拉海纳有超过 271 座建筑遭到损坏或毁坏。拉海纳是夏威夷王国历史悠久的前首都，位于毛伊岛西海岸，现已成为热门旅游目的地。毛伊岛内陆地区（包括哈雷阿卡拉国家公园）至少 1,000 英亩的土地已被烧焦。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833197?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周三，毛伊岛拉海纳市海滨的建筑物、树木和船只被野火摧毁。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：梅森·贾维/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>据联邦紧急事务管理局称，毛伊岛西部约有 11,000 人断电，手机和固定电话服务也已中断。毛伊县官员表示，周三晚间没有针对三场火灾发布新的疏散命令或遏制估计。</p><p> FEMA 表示，截至周四上午，毛伊岛的 6 个避难所已容纳 2000 多人。其中一个避难所位于毛伊岛高中，疏散人员睡在地板上的垫子上。其他人则选择睡在学校停车场的车里。</p><p>周三，伊夫·赫卢 (Yves Helou) 和亚里娜·扬查克 (Yaryna Yanchak) 在拉海纳郊外的酒店缺乏食物和水后，在毛伊岛高中过夜。</p><p>他们表示，由于没有手机服务，他们最初并不知道席卷拉海纳和附近社区的大规模野火。两人说，酒店工作人员只告诉他们，高速公路附近发生了灌木丛火灾。</p><p> “我们是无意中来到这里的，”来自芝加哥的 31 岁的 Helou 说。 “我们只是出去寻找食物。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>由于道路封闭，他们无法进入度假村，他们的行李和扬查克的护照已经回到度假村，两人还无法安排离开毛伊岛。他们希望周四晚些时候离开。</p><p>在联邦团队的支持下，毛伊岛的搜救工作正在进行，8,250 人已被命令撤离该岛。直升机一直在拉海纳上空喷水以控制火势。州和县当局敦促游客远离或离开。夏威夷交通部部长埃德·斯尼芬 (Ed Sniffen) 表示，周三有超过 11,000 名旅客以及约 400 名航空公司工作人员离开毛伊岛。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833199?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周三晚上，毛伊岛的卡胡卢伊机场挤满了人，数千人试图离开该岛。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：里克·鲍默/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周三晚上，毛伊岛的卡胡卢伊机场挤满了人，数千人试图离开该岛。有些人睡在航站楼里。夏威夷航空运营从机场飞往檀香山的深夜航班，帮助人们撤离该岛。周四，该航空公司增加了 4 趟航班，并提供从毛伊岛出发的 19 美元折扣机票，以帮助紧急离开的人们。</p><p>亚当·温特劳布 (Adam Weintraub) 表示，救援队评估烧毁地区时可能会造成更多人员伤亡。</p>周四，夏威夷紧急事务管理局发言人在“早安美国”节目中。<p></p><p> “我们希望得到最好的结果，但我们也做好了最坏的准备，”他说。</p><p>海岸警卫队表示，已救出14名逃入大海躲避烟雾和火焰的人。</p><p>拜登总统周四宣布夏威夷发生重大灾难，并批准了州长协助应对和恢复工作的请求。州长乔什·格林说，该声明还包括为毛伊县居民寻求临时住房和房屋维修提供资金。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="935" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833115?width=1260&amp;height=935" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">夏威夷毛伊岛拉海纳地区 Banyan Court 山火的卫星图像。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Maxar Technologies </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="935" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833114?width=1260&amp;height=935" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">野火袭击前的同一地区。在彩色红外卫星图像中，烧毁的区域显示为黑色和灰色，而健康的植被显示为红色阴影。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Maxar Technologies</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “我保证不遗余力地扑灭破坏性的野火，为流离失所者提供庇护，治疗和安慰受创伤的人，支持我们的急救人员，恢复通讯线路，并争取我们联邦和县合作伙伴的援助，以应对这一历史性的灾难。”一生的灾难，”格林说。</p><p>今年夏天，野火和其他形式的极端天气席卷了世界多个地区。大火席卷了希腊、葡萄牙和加拿大，而中国则面临着严重的洪水和灼热的热浪。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-2023-hottest-month-record-climate-change-5e5b3097?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">七月是世界上有记录以来最热的月份</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="672" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/ce8ee128-0322-47e6-8c1b-480d6a6040aa-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>拉海纳各地闷烧瓦砾的视频片段显示了破坏的规模。建筑物、棕榈树和汽车被火焰吞没，风吹过的火墙和烟雾蔓延到整个城镇。受灾地区包括前街，这​​是一条深受游客欢迎的不拘一格的道路，两旁遍布商店、企业和历史建筑。</p><p> 1800 年代中期，水手和船只停泊在历史悠久的捕鲸小镇拉海纳。其历史街区是国家历史名胜名录的一部分。据拉海纳修复基金会称，鲍德温故居博物馆是拉海纳的地标，是毛伊岛最古老的房屋。一棵树龄 150 年的巨大榕树是拉海纳市中心的中心景观，于 1873 年被带到岛上。据该镇网站称，这棵树在火灾中受损。</p><p>副州长西尔维娅·卢克周三发布紧急公告，鼓励暂停飞往毛伊岛的所有非必要航空旅行。格林出差归来期间，卢克担任代理州长，他启动了夏威夷国民警卫队以帮助应对工作。</p><p> “我们正在不懈努力，确保每个受影响者的健康和安全，”卢克在参加对损失的空中评估后在周三晚间发表的一份声明中表示。 “虽然我们深爱的拉海纳已经永远改变，但社区的爱和阿罗哈是坚定不移的。”</p><p>周三，夏威夷大岛也发生了三场野火，但当局没有报告任何人死亡。周三晚上，夏威夷县官员取消了与火灾有关的所有强制疏散。</p><p>当局表示，他们已为周二飓风多拉的到来做好准备，但尚未为随后发生的野火做好准备。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833195?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">视频片段显示，拉海纳的建筑物、棕榈树和汽车被大火吞没。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：JEFF MELICHAR/TMX/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>夏威夷国防部副将肯尼思·哈拉少将表示，长期干燥、低湿度和大风助长了野火。</p><p>毛伊岛是夏威夷第二大旅游岛屿，仅次于欧胡岛。根据该州商业、经济发展和旅游部的数据，毛伊岛今年上半年接待游客近 150 万人次，较 2022 年同期增长 5.7%。同期游客总支出为 34.7 亿美元，比去年增长约 25%。</p><p> “这将是一条漫长的复苏之路，”卢克在新闻发布会上说。 “我们对毛伊岛发生的悲剧深感悲痛，尤其是那些失去家人和朋友的人。”</p><p>哈拉指示那些想要寻找亲人的人前往毛伊岛紧急事务管理局。</p><p> — <em>Allison Pohle 对本文做出了贡献。</em></p><p>写信给 Alicia A. Caldwell ( <a href="mailto:alicia.caldwell@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alicia.caldwell@wsj.com</a> )、Michael Wright ( <a href="mailto:michael.wright@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">michael.wright@wsj.com</a> ) 和 Jennifer Calfas ( <a href="mailto:jennifer.calfas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jennifer.calfas@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 17:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7<author><![CDATA[Alicia A. CaldwellJennifer CalfasMichael Wright]]></author><category> WSJSpeeddesk</category><category>野火</category><category>野火</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>飓风/台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>飓风</category><category>台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[CPI Report Shows Annual Inflation of 3.2% in July]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>潜在价格压力的稳定月度数据可能会阻止美联储加息。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122083"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><img width="600" height="750" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833214?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122083"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/amara-omeokwe" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿马拉·奥梅奥奎</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日上午 8:51（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-july-inflation-a4a0a670"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国 7 月份年度通胀有所上升，但本月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-cpi-report-inflation-08-10-2023?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">潜在价格压力</a>仍然温和，可能会阻止美联储在 9 月份加息。</p><p>美国劳工部周四表示，衡量整个经济的商品和服务价格的<a href="https://www.bls.gov/news.release/pdf/cpi.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">消费者价格指数</a>7 月份同比上涨 3.2%，高于截至 6 月份的全年 3%。所谓的核心价格（不包括波动较大的食品和能源类别）7 月份同比上涨 4.7%，较 6 月份 4.8% 的涨幅略有回落。</p><p>然而，月度数据为当前价格趋势提供了更令人鼓舞的景象。 7月份CPI小幅上涨0.2%，与6月份持平。更好的是，核心 CPI 在两个月内也仅上涨 0.2%，这表明通胀并未开始复苏。美联储官员关注核心通胀，因为他们认为核心通胀比总体通胀率更能预测未来通胀。</p><p>特别是核心消费者物价指数可能会鼓励美联储在 9 月政策会议上维持基准利率稳定。新数据将三个月核心通胀年化率降至 3.1%，这是自 2021 年 3 月以来通胀飙升之前的最低读数。</p><p>美联储官员<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">已将利率提高至 22 年来的高位，</a>以通过冷却经济来降低通胀。他们正在关注通胀和其他经济数据，并权衡是否在九月中旬开会时再次加息。其中包括劳工部关于<a href="https://www.bls.gov/news.release/pdf/cpi.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">消费者价格指数</a>的报告，这是整个经济中最受广泛关注的商品和服务价格衡量指标之一。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831800?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美联储官员看到了一些令人鼓舞的迹象，表明价格压力正在缓解。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·扎鲁博夫斯基/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>通货膨胀数学和基本效应</h3><p>《华尔街日报》调查的经济学家估计，7月份CPI环比上涨0.2%，与6月份持平，表明物价压力保持稳定。根据预测，这意味着 7 月份 12 个月通胀率将从 6 月份的 3% 攀升至约 3.3%，这是两年多以来最慢的增速。经济学家表示，这一增长可能与 2022 年 6 月和 7 月发生的情况有很大关系，这是比较的基础。</p><p>年度通胀率于 2022 年 6 月达到 9.1% 的峰值，然后在接下来的几个月中放缓。</p><p>这使得即使月度增长规模保持稳定，今年 7 月的同比比较也可能会出现加速。</p><p>经济学家表示，这种所谓的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-base-effects-trip-up-our-understanding-of-the-economy-66fde398?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">基数效应</a>是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">6 月份年度通胀率较 5 月份下降</a>的部分原因，并且在 2024 年初之前可能不会大幅放缓。他们表示，如果每月价格变化与六月份一样温和，那么未来几个月这一速度可能会加快。</p><p>考虑到这些统计异常，七月份同比增速的增长并不一定表明<strong>&nbsp;</strong>劳拉·罗斯纳 (Laura Rosner) 表示，最近的通胀放缓正在逆转，</p>研究和咨询公司 MacroPolicy Perspectives 的创始人兼高级经济学家。此外，罗斯纳表示，月度增长 0.2% 将被视为符合美联储官员希望看到的温和通胀。<p></p><h3>核心通胀可能保持稳定</h3><p>经济学家估计，所谓的核心价格（不包括波动较大的食品和能源类别）7 月份较 6 月份上涨 0.2%，较上年同期上涨 4.8%，与 6 月份相同。美联储官员关注核心通胀，因为他们认为核心通胀比总体通胀率更能预测未来通胀。</p><p>在经济从疫情中复苏之初，租金和二手车价格大幅上涨。但七月和未来几个月应该会显示<strong>&nbsp;</strong>租金通胀持续放缓和二手车价格下降， <strong>&nbsp;</strong> Nationwide首席经济学家Kathy Bostjancic表示，这将给核心通胀带来下行压力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=FB57A5A0-E270-46D2-B5D4-3ED0269F546E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fconsumer-price-index-report-july-inflation-a4a0a670&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">本周发布的内容包括 CPI 通胀报告、UPS 和迪士尼的盈利报告。最新的消费者信贷报告和季度家庭债务数据也在预期之中。 《华尔街日报》的 Dion Rabouin 对此进行了详细分析。照片：乔·雷德尔/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>美联储还关注什么</h3><p>尽管美联储官员看到了一些令人鼓舞的迹象，表明物价压力正在缓解，但经济<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">却出乎意料地出现了大幅放缓</a>。美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔表示，央行正在寻求劳动力市场进一步疲软，包括工资增长放缓。</p><p>工资压力是美联储也在密切关注通胀指标的部分原因，该指标主要关注不包括能源和住房在内的劳动密集型服务业。所谓的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-is-supercore-inflation-11675195498?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">超级核心通胀</a>和整体核心通胀在 7 月份可能不会大幅放缓，因为机票和酒店价格可能没有像 6 月份那样快速降温，他说</p>普贾·斯里拉姆 (Pooja Sriram)，巴克莱银行美国经济学家。<p></p><p>斯里拉姆表示，不包括汽车在内的核心商品通胀趋势也可能表明，早期的供应链问题和大流行造成的其他干扰是否正在继续消退。</p><h3> 7月汽油价格</h3><p>根据能源数据和分析提供商 OPIS 的数据，7 月份美国每加仑普通无铅汽油的平均价格从月初的约 3.54 美元逐渐攀升至月底的 3.76 美元。经济学家表示，由于消费者价格指数基本上是基于本月平均价格，因此近期汽油价格的上涨可能会对八月份的通胀数据产生更大的影响。</p><p>写信给 Amara Omeokwe： <a href="mailto:amara.omeokwe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">amara.omeokwe@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/3edd1a82-cda0-47b5-81bf-89e82fb91993.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 12:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-july-inflation-a4a0a670</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-july-inflation-a4a0a670<author><![CDATA[Amara Omeokwe]]></author><category>通货膨胀</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字/价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>消费者价格指数</category><category>通货膨胀</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字</category><category>价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>消费者价格指数</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Some 911 Call Centers Still Haven’t Adapted to the Cellphone]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在全国范围内，许多 911 中心很难定位手机呼叫者，也无法接收短信或照片，因为这些系统仍然依赖已有数十年历史的传统电话线<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122137"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="494" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832844?width=700&amp;height=494" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">遗留系统的持续使用给呼叫中心运营商带来了一系列挑战，包括呼叫错误路由。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Rose Baca/达拉斯晨报/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122137"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/isabelle-bousquette" itemprop="url" rel="author">伊莎贝尔·布斯克特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 10 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-911-call-centers-still-havent-adapted-to-the-cellphone-41fbd195"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>手机问世几十年后，一些 911 中心仍在努力实现其通信基础设施的现代化，这是资金短缺和对做出改变的高风险犹豫不决的结果。</p><p>但是，在付费电话遍布城市各个角落并且每个家庭都有固定电话时安装的遗留系统的继续使用给呼叫中心运营商带来了一系列挑战，包括呼叫错误路由，可能会增加响应时间。</p><p>美国监管机构估计，仅将<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/911-response-times-are-getting-faster-thanks-to-data-integration-11560468747?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">911 响应时间缩短</a>一分钟，每年就可以挽救多达 10,000 人的生命。</p><p>该国拥有 5,500 多个呼叫中心，通常由当地资助和运营，每个呼叫中​​心都走了自己的现代化道路。总体进展缓慢。</p><p> “我们现在使用已有 35 年历史的技术来拨打 911 电话，”俄勒冈州应急管理部项目运营团队负责人 Patrick Lustig 说。 “除了 911 系统之外，其他一切都发生了变化。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>非营利组织国家紧急号码协会于 2004 年提出了建立“下一代 911”中心的愿景，该中心可以充分利用现代功能。下一代 911 的核心是从仅支持语音通信的铜质电话基础设施转变为基于互联网的网络，能够接收各种类型的数字数据，包括更准确的呼叫者位置信息以及照片和视频——一旦适当的软件位于顶部。此后几年，NENA 发布了一系列下一代 911 标准。</p><p>据咨询公司 Frost &amp; Sullivan 称，到 2022 年底，下一代 911 技术的部署覆盖了约 56.2% 的美国人口。</p><p>对于剩下的 43.8% 的人口来说，升级可能还需要几年的时间才能形成。与此同时，他们还得应对已有数十年历史的系统的局限性。</p><h3>呼叫路由和位置</h3><p>密苏里州克里斯蒂安县紧急服务 911 执行董事贝基·培根 (Becky Bacon) 表示，不精确的呼叫路由是在旧通信基础设施上运行的呼叫中心面临的最大问题之一。</p><p> NENA 估计，每年有 2700 万个遗留系统上的呼叫被错误路由，浪费了宝贵的时间，因为接线员随后必须将呼叫者转移到适当的中心。</p><p>为全国 911 中心提供网络、软件和服务的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSI" class="">摩托罗拉解决方案</a>公司副总裁 Lynne Houserman 表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>与注册到特定地址的固定电话不同，手机的位置通常由处理呼叫的信号塔来确定。 。她说，然后根据数十年历史的数据库将呼叫路由到 911 中心，该数据库将蜂窝基站与呼叫中心位置联系起来。</p><p>但她表示，蜂窝基站的边界并不精确，有时会落入多个 911 中心的管辖范围内，这意味着电话并不总是会路由到最近的中心。豪瑟曼说：“你可能就在西雅图警察局的隔壁，但由于你的电话恰好发生了阴谋，所以你就进入了金县 911。”</p><p>但手机中的软件可以传输更精确的位置，就像优步或谷歌地图一样。过去十年，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">苹果</a></p>谷歌以及其他设备制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-to-push-fix-for-locating-911-callers-1529314200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一直致力于将这些信息提供</a>给紧急服务部门。然而，传统 911 中心通常无法利用它来进行呼叫路由。<p></p><p> “那个设备知道它在哪里。只是 911 中心目前无法接收该信息。”俄勒冈州的勒斯蒂格说道。</p><p>俄勒冈州 911 项目经理 Frank Kuchta 表示，一旦下一代升级启用基于设备的路由，911 接线员在接听电话时也会自动接收该设备特定的位置。如今，如果设备所有者选择加入，传统设置可以通过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/startup-seeks-to-solve-911s-biggest-riddle-pinpointing-cellphone-callers-1493112780?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">RapidSOS 等其他服务提供商</a>访问它，但同样，这对路由没有帮助，他说。</p><h3>短信和多媒体</h3><p>2007 年弗吉尼亚理工大学<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB117673757830671289?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">发生枪击事件</a>时，学生和目击者纷纷向 911 拨打短信。由于 911 中心没有接收短信的设备，所以无人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/BL-DGB-19828?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">接听</a>。</p><p>据 NENA 称，16 年后，该国约 40% 至 45% 的 911 中心仍然无法接受短信，该机构称短信在敏感情况下至关重要，包括家庭暴力事件以及听力障碍人士。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="393" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832714?width=700&amp;height=393" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 911 调度员控制台显示与下一代 911 呼叫处理集成的云服务。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：摩托罗拉解决方案</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>豪瑟曼说，有了下一代 911 网络，短信功能就会自动启用，尽管也有一些临时方法可以使其在没有完整网络的情况下工作。</p><p>下一代 911 网络还使 911 中心能够从手机接收照片、视频或流媒体视频，并与急救人员共享这些内容。</p><p> 911 中心表示，这些新功能对于让他们赶上人们在生活其他方面习惯的沟通方式至关重要。</p><p> “我认为我可以通过短信向我妈妈发送某件事的照片，这真是太棒了，但我不能将活跃枪击者的照片发送给 911，这有点疯狂，”Aleisha Rucker 说道。赖特，佐治亚州紧急通信局副执行主任。</p><h3>向前进</h3><p>NENA 表示，资金仍然是投资必要的 911 系统升级的主要障碍。</p><p>豪瑟曼表示，大多数州都征收 911 税，这通常只够维持现有的遗留系统，而不是投资于重大升级，但在某些情况下甚至不够，尽管有些州已经成功寻求增加税收。俄勒冈州能够在 2020 年将 75 美分的税收提高到 1 美元，在 2021 年提高到 1.25 美元。</p><p> “资金是关键。许多州和司法管辖区没有资金能力来采购这些大型、昂贵、冗余的系统，”俄勒冈州的库赫塔说。</p><p>作为《中产阶级减税和创造就业法案》的一部分，自 2012 年 1.09 亿美元以来，联邦一直没有向下一代 911 项目提供资金。今年早些时候，众议院和参议院都提出了新的拨款法案。</p><p> 2018 年提交给国会的一份报告估计，在全国范围内部署下一代 911 基础设施将花费 95 亿至 127 亿美元。</p><p> “立法者并没有优先考虑我们国家 911 技术的现代化，但他们需要这样做，”摩托罗拉解决方案执行副总裁兼首席技术官 Mahesh Saptharishi 表示。</p><p>在佐治亚州，拉克-赖特表示，该州的紧急通信管理局一直在努力对政策制定者和利益相关者进行下一代 911 教育。她告诉他们这样的话：“如果你打电话订购送货服务或叫 Uber，他们会确切地知道到哪里去找您……不幸的是，我们当前的 911 系统无法找到您。”</p><p>但 911 中心表示，即使有了这些资金，其他障碍仍然存在，包括对 911 员工进行升级系统培训以及获得地方政府的支持。最后，911 中心对对民众至关重要的系统进行任何重大改变都非常犹豫和恐惧。</p><p>密苏里州的培根表示，当事情看起来进展顺利时，很难获得足够的资金和支持来投资升级。 “但确实，电信公司的很多东西都不再起作用了，”她说。</p><p>写信给 Isabelle Bousquette，邮箱为<a href="mailto:isabelle.bousquette@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">isabelle.bousquette@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-911-call-centers-still-havent-adapted-to-the-cellphone-41fbd195</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-911-call-centers-still-havent-adapted-to-the-cellphone-41fbd195<author><![CDATA[Isabelle Bousquette]]></author><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>电信设备</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>电话呼叫中心</category><category>行政/支持服务</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>手机/移动电话</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>移动设备</category><category>技术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>电信设备</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>电话呼叫中心</category><category>行政的</category><category>支持服务</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>细胞</category><category>手机</category><category>移动设备</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Colleges Spend Like There’s No Tomorrow. ‘These Places Are Just Devouring Money.’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>学生们为旗舰州立大学买单，这些大学将资金投入到新建筑和项目中，几乎没有受到任何阻力<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833009/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供； iStock<span>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供；股票</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108095"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108095"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/melissa-korn" itemprop="url" rel="author">Melissa Korn</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/andrea-fuller" itemprop="url" rel="author">Andrea Fuller</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jennifer-s-forsyth" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jennifer S. Forsyth</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 10 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-university-tuition-increase-spending-41a58100"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>美国最著名的公立大学一直在无限制地花钱。在过去的二十年里，他们建造了新的天际线，包括时髦的学术建筑和宿舍。他们向大型体育项目投入巨资，并聘请了多层管理人员。</p><p>然后他们将法案传递给学生。</p><p>肯塔基大学将其校园升级为十多年来每天花费 805,000 美元。其新生<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/many-colleges-fail-in-push-to-boost-enrollment-of-lower-income-students-11663164001?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">来自美国最贫穷的州之一</a>，2021-22 学年的入学费用平均为 18,693 美元。</p><p>宾夕法尼亚州立大学花费了太多的钱，现在陷入了预算危机——尽管它是美国最昂贵的公立大学之一</p><p>俄克拉荷马大学的学费上涨幅度最大，同时花费数百万美元用于项目，包括为其海外​​留学项目收购和翻修一座 32,000 平方英尺的意大利修道院。</p><p>这项支出与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nyu-college-graduate-parent-student-loans-11639618241?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国 1.6 万亿美元的联邦学生债务危机</a>有着千丝万缕的联系。大学通过提高学费来投入资金，这让许多学生别无选择，只能承担更多债务。这意味着学生贷款可以为大学项目提供轻松的融资。</p><p> “学生们现在没有资源来继续为大学想做的所有事情买单，”俄克拉荷马州 2023 届毕业生克里斯平·南 (Crispin South) 说。 “你不能仅仅通过向学生求助来继续增加收入。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1500" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/1980839d-de93-4796-9018-4224bb39ebf9-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>美国家庭长期以来都清楚，大学费用已经上涨，即使是那些旨在让州居民负担得起的公立学校也是如此。为了找出根本原因，《华尔街日报》检查了 2002 年以来 50 所旗舰大学（通常是各州最古老的公立学校）的财务报表，并根据通货膨胀进行了调整。</p><p> 2002 年至 2022 年间，中位旗舰大学的支出增长了 38%。</p><p>在《华尔街日报》的分析中，只有一所学校——爱达荷大学——的支出较少。</p><p>学校通过收取学费来支付部分费用。 The median flagship received more than double the revenue from undergraduate and graduate tuition and fees it did 20 years prior. Even accounting for enrollment gains, that amounted to a 64% price increase for the average student, far outpacing the growth in most big household expenses.</p><h3> More tuition revenue</h3><p> Public university leaders often blame stingier state funding for the need to raise tuition revenue. And three-fourths of states did cut their support, undermining a longstanding principle that schools educated the populace with government backing. But universities generally didn&#39;t tighten their belts as a result. Rather, they raised prices far beyond what was needed to fill the hole.</p><p> For every $1 lost in state support at those universities over the two decades, the median school increased tuition and fee revenue by nearly $2.40, more than covering the cuts, the Journal found. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1334" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/5c3441d8-64ed-4f87-b10e-dbf69fcfa3da-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Through it all, schools operated in a culture that valued unrelenting growth and prioritized raising revenue over cutting costs. Administrators established ambitious strategic plans and tried to lure wealthy students with luxurious amenities. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-news-college-rankings-yale-law-fe24f0b2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Influential college rankings rewarded</a> those that spent more.</p><p> Many university officials struggled to understand their own budgets and simply increased spending every year. Trustees demanded little accountability and often rubber-stamped what came before them. And schools inconsistently disclose what they spend, making it nearly impossible for the public to review how their tuition and tax dollars are being used.</p><p> “These places are just devouring money,” said Holden Thorp, who was chancellor at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill from 2008 to 2013 and is now editor in chief of Science. Offering everything to everyone all at once is unsustainable, he said. “Universities need to focus on what their true priorities are and what they were created to do,” he said.</p><p> Colleges invested money inside and outside the classroom, including to improve technology, expand counseling and intramural sports, and build facilities such as modern dorms and new stadiums.</p><p> To examine public university spending, the Journal collected data from audits, archived budget websites and documents received through public-records requests covering expenses in fiscal 2002, 2012 and 2022.</p><p> Much of the increase in outlays showed up in the hiring process, for administrators, faculty, coaches and finance experts, the Journal&#39;s analysis found. Salaries and benefits, which usually eat up more than half of operating budgets, rose by roughly 40% at the median flagship since 2002. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829618?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The University of Kentucky&#39;s student center last month.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jon Cherry for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829601?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Computers for videogames in Kentucky&#39;s new Esports Lounge.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jon Cherry for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The University of Florida in 2022 had more than 50 employees with titles of director, associate director or assistant director of communications, roughly double the number it had in 2017. The school also employed more than 160 assistant, associate, executive and other types of deans last year, up from about 130 in 2017.</p><p> Spokesman Steve Orlando said the university is decentralized and different departments have the freedom to hire as they need.</p><p> Inflation-adjusted spending on athletic coaches rose by about half between 2010 and 2022 at the median flagship, the Journal&#39;s analysis of data from the Knight-Newhouse College Athletics Database found. The Journal used data from the period with the most complete figures.</p><p> Though a handful of powerhouse sports departments pay for themselves, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/march-madness-is-a-moneymaker-most-schools-still-operate-in-red-11615545002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">most can break even only with student fees and university subsidies</a> .</p><p> Across all flagships with available data, that additional funding totaled $632 million in 2022. That&#39;s a jump of 27% from 12 years prior.</p><p> The University of Connecticut won the national championship this spring in men&#39;s basketball, and its women&#39;s team has been a near-constant presence in the Final Four. Yet since 2016, Connecticut&#39;s athletic department has received more than $35 million annually in student fees and university subsidies to stay afloat. In 2022, it took in $55 million in such funds, making up more than half its total athletics budget.</p><p> The school said more than $13 million of that subsidy covered a payout to a former men&#39;s basketball coach as part of a legal settlement over his employment contract, and that it faces unique challenges in having to pay rent and other fees for basketball and hockey games, which are played off campus.</p><p> Overall, the University of Connecticut&#39;s spending rose by 73% between 2002 and 2022, far faster than enrollment grew. Much of that was driven by personnel costs, with spending on benefits more than tripling.</p><p> Reka Wrynn, associate vice president of budget, planning and institutional research, said that was in part because the school was on the hook for a growing share of the state&#39;s unfunded pension liability. Connecticut was also obligated to pay for raises that unionized employees negotiated with the state, she said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829597?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> University of Connecticut&#39;s basketball team during the NCAA women&#39;s tournament in March.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sean Elliot/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> Little accountability</h3><p> Colleges have faced little accountability over their budgets in part because they aren&#39;t required to track expenses in a uniform way. And Education Department data on college finances often contain errors and don&#39;t match audited figures.</p><p> Schools use their own discretion to categorize spending on audited financial statements, making precise comparisons at a single school over time, or among different schools, extremely difficult. Colleges, for example, sometimes classify professors&#39; salaries as instructional spending one year and as research expenses the next.</p><p> Universities view audits “more as a requirement than a tool for the public,” said Robert Kelchen, an education professor at the University of Tennessee at Knoxville who researches university finance.</p><p> The growth in schools&#39; spending was particularly aggressive between 2002 and 2012, with total operating expenses rising a median 30%. Some schools began to pull back on spending in the subsequent decade, under the dual financial pressures of a recession and pandemic. Amid national outcry about student debt, they also slowed the rate at which they increased tuition.</p><p> But spending still climbed. Total operating expenses rose nearly 10% from 2012 to 2022 at the median university.</p><p> In some cases, colleges spent more as the student body grew, with the typical flagship increasing enrollment by about 20% over the past two decades. Adding students may in some cases be expensive—requiring new dorms and classroom space—or relatively inexpensive, especially for online students. Nonetheless, spending per student rose, by a median 15% over the past two decades.</p><p> The schools have passed the tab on to students even in the nation&#39;s poorest states. Most of these schools increased financial aid for low-income students, but that hasn&#39;t fully offset rising tuition for many families.</p><p> Kentucky has among the country&#39;s lowest median household income. What in-state students paid in 2021-22 put Kentucky in the top half of flagship schools ranked by cost. Those figures, from the Education Department, cover what the average freshman paid in tuition, fees, room and board after scholarships.</p><p> Kentucky on its website touts the total of $3.66 billion spent on its Lexington campus overhaul over the past dozen years. That included new homes for the law, business and visual-arts schools, state-of-the-art hospital facilities, a student center, a 900-spot parking garage, a theater for videogame competitions and dorms sporting full-size Tempur-Pedic mattresses, granite countertops and in-unit washer-dryers.</p><p> Private developers were involved in some projects but more than half of the total construction costs were paid for with university funds.</p><p> “Our residence halls meet student and family needs and expectations, while emphasizing learning and connectedness,” university spokesman Jay Blanton said. He said that some features in the dorms, such as the countertops, lower maintenance expenses, and that the Tempur-Pedic mattresses were purchased at a comparable cost to traditional ones.</p><p> The school set out decades ago to become one of the best universities in the country. Specifically, it targeted a spot among the top 20 public schools that conduct research and offer doctoral degrees, according to a 1997 state mandate. Despite the directive, the legislature began reducing its funding. Over 20 years, appropriations fell by nearly half. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829623?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The exterior of Kentucky&#39;s student center, which was upgraded and expanded in recent years. The school spent $3.66 billion since 2011 to remake its campus.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jon Cherry for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829599?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Construction at the Kentucky campus in July.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jon Cherry for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “We will not trim our aspirations,” President Eli Capilouto said in 2016. “But we do have to find more creative ways to power our progress.” Kentucky boosted research funding and faculty salaries, which helped it attract talent.</p><p> Some college rankings, including US News &amp; World Report, reward spending in those categories as well as student services such as clubs and cultural events. They don&#39;t necessarily credit moves that make schools more efficient. The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/college-rankings-list-2022-11632246093?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Journal&#39;s college rankings</a> also took spending into consideration, though it is dropping that measure in coming reports.</p><p> For all Kentucky&#39;s effort, US News ranked the school No. 64 among public universities in 2022, actually dropping a few spots from where it had been a decade earlier.</p><p> But the bill for students grew. Kentucky took in about 70% more in tuition and fee revenue per student than it did 20 years ago.</p><p> In 2017, Rowan Reid was Kentucky&#39;s student government president and held a seat on the university board. When asked to vote for a 4% increase on tuition for in-state undergraduates, she urged her fellow board members to hold the school more accountable.</p><p> “We address efficiencies only to a point where we can pass on the remaining deficit to students,” Reid said at the time. “To me this feels wrong.”</p><p> The tuition increase passed 16 to one, with Reid as the only “no” vote. Looking back this spring on her time with the board, Reid said she had a mandate to look out for students&#39; interests but was torn as to how she could reconcile that with what was best for the university.</p><p> The school said it has decelerated the rate of increase for tuition and fees over the past several years, and students from the lowest-income families receive scholarship support.</p><p> Blanton said Kentucky continues to grow and aspire to be recognized as one of the best public research institutions in the country but has shifted to a broader focus of advancing the state.</p><h3> Battle for the best students</h3><p> Schools loaded their campuses with state-of-the-art recreation centers and dorms to appeal to students with top test scores and minimal need for financial aid. The price for these amenities was then baked into the bills for all students, including with fees students paid to cover construction debt.</p><p> Tuition and fee revenue per student climbed by double digits in the past 20 years at every school in the Journal&#39;s analysis. The average student paid more because many schools both upped prices and increased the percentage of higher-paying students from out of state. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="3268" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/4e1b3086-4f54-4f8b-ad64-239b2396927d-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> At the University of Oklahoma, per-student tuition and fees rose 166%, the most of any flagship. The school also borrowed hundreds of millions of dollars to perform building upgrades and erect new dormitories.</p><p> “We levered up the balance sheet to avoid dealing with [financial] reality,” said Oklahoma President Joseph Harroz Jr. , who took the helm in 2019. Across higher education, he said, “there was an arms race.”</p><p> Beginning in 2009, the university spent $14.3 million to buy and renovate a monastery in Arezzo, Italy, to house a new study-abroad program. The monastery has a landscaped garden, faculty apartment and classrooms featuring painted frescoes.</p><p> The school said it was paid for by a mix of private gifts and university funds.</p><p> “Would I go and do one of those right now? No,” Harroz said. “It wouldn&#39;t be the best use of capital dollars.”</p><p> Harroz said that under some of his predecessors, the school didn&#39;t maintain long-term budget plans or prioritize its needs over its wishes. Oklahoma has since changed course, he said, and the university cut $143 million in expenses at the main campus in Norman since 2018.</p><p> The increase in tuition at Oklahoma came after the state legislature gave school regents tuition-setting authority in the early 2000s, a move designed to allow the school to catch up with its peers&#39; rates, said University of Oklahoma spokeswoman April Sandefer. She said its increases have slowed in recent years, and more than half of Oklahoma undergraduates leave school debt-free thanks to a growing financial-aid budget.</p><h3> License to spend</h3><p> Research by James V. Koch, an economist who studies college spending and a former president at Old Dominion University in Virginia, found that public-university trustees approved 98% of the cost-increasing proposals they reviewed, often unanimously. In most states, he said, there hasn&#39;t been anyone to say, “No, you can&#39;t do that.”</p><p> Back in 2005, a Hawaii state audit called out the University of Hawaii System board for approving a budget that gave the flagship Manoa campus $200 million when, auditors said, all but $13 million went to vague or unnecessary requests.</p><p> Honolulu attorney Benjamin Kudo, who joined the university&#39;s board in 2011, said he was stunned by the lack of information he was given during the budget process. He said he received a packet of pie charts and a PowerPoint presentation with general information on how the university planned to divide up its funds for areas including teaching, libraries, athletics and facilities across 10 campuses. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829600?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The University of Oklahoma&#39;s campus in Arezzo, Italy.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The University of Oklahoma </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829596?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Norman campus at Oklahoma. The school borrowed hundreds of millions of dollars to perform building upgrades and erect new dormitories.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alamy</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Kudo said administrators weren&#39;t initially receptive to requests that he and another new board member, Jan Sullivan, made for more detail, including a comparison of projected versus actual spending. Kudo, who served on the board until 2022, recalled being accused of trying to micromanage the $1 billion budget.</p><p> School officials expected him to follow the lead of prior trustees, Kudo said: “It&#39;s basically an automatic approval of whatever the administration wants.”</p><p> Sullivan also said such rubber stamping was typical early in her tenure. After a few years of nagging, Sullivan and Kudo said, the board received more detailed financial information, and it stopped greenlighting so many requests.</p><p> University of Hawaii President David Lassner said the university has changed. He decried a time around a decade ago, shortly after he was named interim president, when the board found out about depleted reserves by reviewing audited financial statements that had been produced six months after the fiscal year closed.</p><p> “That is no way to understand the financial health of something as big and complicated as this,” he said. “We&#39;re certainly not budgeting by pie charts anymore.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="464" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831288?width=700&amp;height=464" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> University of Hawaii President David Lassner, center, at the ceremony to officially name him president of the school in 2014.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: University of Hawaii</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> &#39;Knee-jerk reaction&#39;</h3><p> Penn State, like many schools, long relied on a simple approach to budgeting, in which each department generally received the same amount of money it got the prior year plus a little more to cover inflation. Dollars were rarely tied to enrollment shifts or demonstrated need.</p><p> The school&#39;s spending rose 36% since 2002. That number excludes the university&#39;s health system, which the Journal removed from its analysis where possible. Total tuition and fee revenue from both undergraduate and graduate students increased 72% over the past two decades, far faster than enrollment grew.</p><p> Penn State&#39;s University Park campus was the country&#39;s most expensive state flagship in the 2021-22 school year for in-state freshmen after scholarships. Those students paid an average $26,747 in tuition, fees, room and board, according to the Education Department data.</p><p> The school said it offers students the option of starting at one of its less expensive regional campuses and finishing at University Park, and has increased financial aid significantly. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1594" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/2b99b9f0-3109-4607-9038-fffbc5ecc301-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Penn State cut spending nearly 3% between 2012 and 2022. Still, the university&#39;s 2022-23 budget forecast spending that was $140 million more than its revenue.</p><p> It&#39;s not the first time expenditures were projected to outpace revenue, and Penn State determined last year it was on track to blow through its $350 million reserve funds in the next few years if it didn&#39;t change course. Trustees gave the administration until 2025 to balance the budget.</p><p> Trustee Barry Fenchak criticized his fellow board members at the meeting when they voted last summer to increase tuition and fees by 5% for in-state students at the University Park campus after the state held funding flat.</p><p> “I think the knee-jerk reaction was, &#39;OK, we&#39;ve got to raise tuition,&#39; and I think perhaps the knee-jerk reaction should have been, &#39;We need to get to work on the things we should&#39;ve been doing for the last 10 years and light a bit of a fire underneath our behinds&#39; ” to address costs, he said.</p><p> Several trustees at the meeting said the decision was based on thorough analysis.</p><p> At meeting after meeting for decades, Penn State board members complained of the state&#39;s anemic support while they simultaneously approved hundreds of millions of dollars in new construction, according to board minutes.</p><p> The university&#39;s state appropriation fell 39% over the past 20 years, and the school receives among the lowest state support per student of US flagships. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831761?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Penn State&#39;s University Park campus in April. The school spent so much money that it now has a budget crisis, even though it&#39;s among the most expensive public universities in the US</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: aul Weaver/Sipa/Reuters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Growth in tuition revenue has more than made up for declining state funding. On a per-student basis, Penn State received nearly $2.25 in additional tuition revenue for every $1 lost in state support, compared with $1.25 in tuition revenue added at the median school.</p><p> “We acknowledge that tuition has increased quite a bit over the past 20 years, which is a large stretch of time for such a comparison when taking into account growth in student needs, services, technology, stem fields, academic support, mental health services etc. and considering our stagnant state funding,” said Lisa Powers, a school spokeswoman.</p><p> Mary Isaacson, a Democrat and chair of the subcommittee on higher education in the Pennsylvania House of Representatives, said that while public funding declined, the school&#39;s aggressive physical growth and lengthy wish list also helped put it on its path to financial insecurity.</p><p> Penn State said much of the construction was necessary to replace aging facilities, and that factors such as inflation and the pandemic drove up costs, too.</p><p> The university said last year it would revise the way it sets its operating budget. The new model, it said, will take into account enrollment changes and available resources, and be data-driven.</p><p> Write to Melissa Korn at <a href="mailto:Melissa.Korn@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Melissa.Korn@wsj.com</a> , Andrea Fuller at <a href="mailto:andrea.fuller@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">andrea.fuller@wsj.com</a> and Jennifer S. Forsyth at <a href="mailto:Jennifer.Forsyth@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jennifer.Forsyth@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>方法</h4><p>To examine colleges&#39; spending patterns, the Journal supplemented figures from audited financial statements from 2002, 2012 and 2022 with data from public information requests and other documents. All numbers in the analysis were adjusted to 2022 dollars. Figures representing the median flagship were calculated by taking the median of the change at each school.</p><p> Some schools said they didn&#39;t keep historical records of every figure the Journal sought, such as salary and benefits spending. The Journal asked colleges to provide information for only the main flagship campus, but not all schools said they were able to do so. The figures for roughly one third of the universities in the Journal&#39;s analysis include data for some branch campuses, with data for several states representing large university systems.</p><p> The Journal asked colleges to exclude health systems and hospital operations from the figures, but not all did so. Health-related expenses can make up a large share of operating budgets, and universities that included hospitals in their figures tended to have among the largest increases in total operating expenses. However, the overall median increase in operating expenses was roughly similar whether or not the Journal included these schools in its analysis.</p><p> Separately, the Journal used data from the Education Department that covered the price in-state students typically paid. These figures, known as net price, cover the average cost of first-time, full-time students who received scholarships.</p><p> Per-student tuition revenue figures, derived from data in audited financial statements, reflect money paid by all students, including graduate and out-of-state. As a result, these calculations don&#39;t match the net-price figures.</p><p> Enrollment figures, also from the Education Department, reflect what is known as full-time equivalent enrollment. To calculate this, the Journal used a formula similar to the Education Department&#39;s method, taking into account the mix of full- and part-time undergraduate and graduate students each fall.</p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-university-tuition-increase-spending-41a58100</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-university-tuition-increase-spending-41a58100<author><![CDATA[Melissa KornAndrea FullerJennifer S. Forsyth]]></author><category> wsjinvestigations</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>领导者</category><category>photo-commission</category><category>教育</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>大学学院</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Career Education</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>career education </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[With AI, Hackers Can Simply Talk Computers Into Misbehaving]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>使用一种称为“即时注入”的技术，黑客可以使用简单的英语破坏人工智能系统<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832001/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供； iStock<span>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供；股票</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001121393"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001121393"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/robert-mcmillan" itemprop="url" rel="author">罗伯特·麦克米伦</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日上午 12:01（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-ai-hackers-can-simply-talk-computers-into-misbehaving-ad488686"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> ChatGPT <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-ai-chatbot-app-explained-11675865177?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">快速有效地响应简单命令的</a>能力吸引了超过 1 亿用户，同时也吸引了一些黑客。</p><p>安全研究员 Johann Rehberger 就是其中之一。他最近用简单的英语诱骗 OpenAI 的聊天机器人做了一些坏事：阅读他的电子邮件，对其进行总结并将该信息发布到互联网上。雷伯格说，如果犯罪分子掌握了这种技术，它可能会被用来窃取某人电子邮件收件箱中的敏感数据。</p><p> Rehberger 表示，ChatGPT“降低了各种攻击的进入门槛”。 “因为你并不真的需要能够编写代码。你不必拥有深厚的计算机科学或黑客知识。”</p><p>此次攻击不会影响大多数 ChatGPT 帐户。它之所以有效，是因为 Rehberger 正在使用<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chat-gpt-open-ai-we-are-tech-guinea-pigs-647d827b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">ChatGPT 的 Beta 测试功能</a>，该功能使其可以访问 Slack、Gmail 等应用程序。</p><p> OpenAI 发言人在一封电子邮件中表示：“我们感谢主动披露调查结果，并已在 ChatGPT 中实施修复程序来阻止这些攻击。” “我们感谢社区为我们提供了重要的反馈，我们可以利用这些反馈来使我们的模型更安全。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B00854AA-74DE-4E8C-8067-E09A4C38D821&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwith-ai-hackers-can-simply-talk-computers-into-misbehaving-ad488686&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">在全国范围内，人工智能聊天机器人现在正在接受快餐得来速订单。 《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩 (Joanna Stern) 在 Hardee&#39;s 对该技术进行了一系列测试，包括发出狗吠声和提出一些疯狂的问题。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>雷伯格的技术被称为“即时注入”，是一种<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hackers-up-their-game-using-chatgpt-fe870ec4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新型网络攻击</a>，随着科技公司将<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-ask-the-right-question-12d0f035?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新一代人工智能软件</a>应用到其业务和消费产品中，这种攻击变得越来越重要。这些方法正在重新定义黑客攻击的含义，安全研究人员正在竞相在人工智能系统的使用变得更广泛之前探测漏洞。</p><p>虚假信息专家担心“数据中毒”攻击，即黑客篡改用于训练人工智能模型的数据，导致误导性结果。其他研究人员担心这些系统中的道德偏见。安全专业人士担心公司机密会通过提取攻击而泄露。安全公司担心人工智能被用来寻找绕过其防御产品的方法。</p><p>几十年来，最后一类攻击一直令人担忧。 2004 年，一位名叫约翰·格雷厄姆-卡明 (John Graham-Cumming) 的研究人员训练了一个人工智能系统，让它学习如何绕过他构建的垃圾邮件过滤器。</p><p>本周晚些时候，由 OpenAI、Google 和 Anthropic 等公司构建的人工智能系统将在拉斯维加斯举行的年度 Defcon 黑客大会上向与会者开放。在那里，一次将邀请多达 150 名黑客对这些系统进行最坏的攻击，最佳攻击者将获得奖励。</p><p> ChatGPT 使用生成式人工智能技术来生成句子，就像类固醇的自动完成工具一样。在幕后，这些工具由简单的语言指令（称为提示）驱动，帮助他们创建非常清晰的答案。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>其中一些指令告诉人工智能系统不要做坏事，比如泄露敏感信息或说冒犯性的话，但像雷伯格这样的黑客已经找到了意想不到的方法来覆盖它们。</p><p>他首先要求聊天机器人总结一个网页，他在网页上写下了“新的重要说明”（全部大写）。</p><p>当 ChatGPT 阅读 Rehberger 所写的内容时，它似乎感到困惑。雷伯格说，他逐渐欺骗机器人遵循一些新命令。 “这就像对系统大喊，‘嘿，这样做！’ ”雷伯格在接受采访时说道。</p><p>自去年 11 月 ChatGPT 发布以来，即时注入攻击激增。人们使用这种技术来欺骗聊天机器人，让其透露其运作的细节，说出令人不安或尴尬的事情，或者在雷伯格的例子中忘记它应该做什么并允许自己重新编程。</p><p>快速注入之所以有效，是因为这些人工智能系统并不总是正确地将系统指令与它们处理的数据分开，说</p>Arvind Narayanan 是普林斯顿大学计算机科学教授。<p></p><p>这些系统的制造商尽最大努力预测它们会如何被滥用，但在本周的会议上，组织者希望通过向数千名黑客开放新技术来学习新技术。 “你不可能测试所有的东西，评估这些模型的唯一方法就是尝试一些东西，看看会发生什么，”活动组织者之一斯文·卡特尔 (Sven Cattell) 说。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>贵公司正在采取哪些措施来防止与人工智能相关的网络威胁？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>黑客们将争夺由<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-ai-is-catapulting-nvidia-toward-the-1-trillion-club-14f42380?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Nvidia</a>驱动的人工智能计算机系统，这些系统将颁发给那些根据赛事评委排名得出最佳黑客方案的人。组织者表示，赚取积分的方式有很多种，包括快速注射、发现人工智能软件中的偏见或破坏其中内置的一些安全机制。</p><p>卡特尔说：“对于人工智能，你需要关注的不仅仅是安全漏洞，因为其危害是深远的，而且更难以诊断和解释。”</p><p>今年 4 月，谷歌将人工智能添加到其 VirusTotal 恶意软件分析服务中。该软件分析上传到系统的所有文件，并使用人工智能编写正在上传的程序的摘要描述。根据《华尔街日报》看到的屏幕截图，几个小时内，一位名叫 Eatscrayon 的匿名黑客修改了犯罪分子使用的工具中的一些代码，并将其上传到 VirusTotal。他的改变欺骗了人工智能系统，将恶意软件描述为“能够创造小狗”。</p><p>谷歌发言人表示，谷歌的人工智能系统最初对 Eatscrayon 上传的代码感到困惑，但后来它学会了更好地检测文件何时被这种方式弄乱。</p><p>普林斯顿大学的纳拉亚南担心，随着科技产品更多地使用生成式人工智能系统，黑客可能会找到新的方法来访问我们的个人数据或计算机系统本身。</p><p> “我们设备上拥有语言模型的应用程序越多，这些应用程序可以决定将数据发送到哪里，这些语言模型被欺骗的途径就越多，”他说。</p><p>写信给罗伯特·麦克米伦<a href="mailto:robert.mcmillan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">robert.mcmillan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-ai-hackers-can-simply-talk-computers-into-misbehaving-ad488686</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-ai-hackers-can-simply-talk-computers-into-misbehaving-ad488686<author><![CDATA[Robert McMillan]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>WSJ插画</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>技术</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>网络犯罪/黑客攻击</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>英伟达</category><category>NVDA</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>网络犯罪</category><category>黑客攻击</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[When You’re the Boss, but Your Employees Make More Money]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Power dynamics get complicated when managers earn less than their employees <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831727/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo Illustration by Andrea D&#39;Aquino for The Wall Street Journal, iStock (5) <span>Photo Illustration by Andrea D&#39;Aquino for The Wall Street Journal, iStock (5)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001118888"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001118888"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/callum-borchers"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-498821" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/callum-borchers" itemprop="url" rel="author">Callum Borchers</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 9, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/higher-salary-workers-boss-manager-157cb4f4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> When NFL quarterback Justin Herbert and NBA star Jaylen Brown signed contracts this summer worth $262.5 million and $304 million, respectively, they struck the richest deals in their leagues&#39; histories. They&#39;re also outearning their bosses by millions a year.</p><p> Professional athletes often command higher salaries than their coaches, since it&#39;s harder to find people to execute plays than diagram them. And individual contributors can earn more than managers in a lot of fields, from finance and tech to sales and media.</p><p> The sticking point is how bosses and their charges deal with those imbalances.</p><p> There are two keys to a functional working relationship when a subordinate makes more money than their manager, people in both camps tell me: The boss must possess the humility to accept the situation and the confidence to project authority. And the highly paid employee can&#39;t be a diva.</p><p> Richard Reice, a labor attorney and chief people officer of a restaurant group, says fat paychecks can lead to entitlement and make a highly paid employee practically unmanageable.</p><p> “Some refuse to do basic things, like attend meetings, just because they think they&#39;re silly,” he says.</p><h3> When leadership doesn&#39;t pay</h3><p> It&#39;s hard to quantify how frequently rank-and-file workers make more than their bosses, but Reice says he has observed a shift from his dual perches in employment law and human resources. Many companies are scrapping the old notion that bigger titles should automatically mean bigger bucks. Instead of promoting star employees into management, where administrative duties can <a href="https://www.wsj.com/podcasts/as-we-work/why-middle-managers-are-feeling-the-squeeze-and-how-to-fix-it/12efb5a7-69ab-477e-848a-9550d381c8dc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">siphon time from their true talents</a> , more businesses are keeping top performers in individual-contributor roles—and paying them like bosses.</p><p> Leadership, in these situations, is considered like any other skill, and not necessarily one that is worth more money.</p><p> We&#39;re more likely to notice now when someone outearns the boss. The pandemic-era rise of distributed teams was accompanied by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-want-to-do-their-jobs-from-anywhere-and-keep-their-big-city-salaries-11631282375?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">cost-of-living adjustments</a> , which meant a manager based in an inexpensive town might earn less than direct reports living in pricier cities.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/salary-ranges-bring-changes-to-the-job-hunt-11665263465?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Pay-transparency laws</a> have given some bosses the jarring experience of seeing less-senior positions at their companies posted on job boards with advertised salaries that exceed their own. Market demand can explain some discrepancies; in other cases, racial, age or gender <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gender-pay-gap-college-11659968901?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">biases could be to blame</a> .</p><h3> Keep your ego in check</h3><p> Nikki Barua, who runs the women&#39;s leadership program Beyond Barriers, says her clients in managerial positions sometimes feel underpaid relative to subordinates and are unsure whether discrimination is a factor. Bosses need to recognize there are often valid reasons behind pay, she says, and advises managers to pay more attention to what their fellow bosses make. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831916?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Nikki Barua runs the women&#39;s leadership program Beyond Barriers.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Emily Cummings</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “The star performer is not the right comparison,” she says.</p><p> Barua says that in previous roles at technology and consulting firms, her knack for bringing in business sometimes led to incentives that pushed her pay over her managers&#39;. She kept her ego in check by viewing her skill as a blessing, remembering that others might be equally good at different jobs that the labor market rewards less generously.</p><p> Now, as an entrepreneur trying to conserve cash, she&#39;s sometimes paid herself less than her employees. She admits that, at times, it was hard not to resent people making more than she did, feeling that she&#39;d be able to draw a salary if only they&#39;d work harder or do better.</p><p> Founders <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-entrepreneurs-should-pay-themselves-1422244851?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">often draw modest salaries</a> , or none at all, in companies&#39; early days, says Jeff Bussgang, general partner in the Boston office of startup investor Flybridge Capital Partners.</p><p> “Naturally, if they own a big chunk of equity, it makes it all more palatable,” he says.</p><p> Plus, owners&#39; status is seldom in doubt, regardless of pay. Berkshire Hathaway CEO Warren Buffett, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/BL-MBB-36218?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">acquired a controlling stake</a> in the company in 1965, has for several decades taken an <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/berkshire-salaries-for-warren-buffett-charlie-munger-unchanged-at-100-000-each-1489790574?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">annual salary of $100,000</a> . His total compensation last year was $401,589, while two vice chairmen earned more than $19 million apiece. Buffett, the world&#39;s sixth-richest person with a net worth of $122 billion, according to the Bloomberg Billionaires Index, derives most of his income from investments.</p><h3> Bosses who earn less</h3><p> Ellen Taaffe, who sits on the compensation committees of several companies, including AARP Services, says corporate boards often set pay by studying the going rates for similar roles in other organizations. Boards can ease potential tension by giving junior executives lower base salaries and enabling them to surpass more senior leaders only through bonuses for exceeding expectations. Usually the people with the loftiest titles make the most money, but not always, notes Taaffe, who teaches at Northwestern University&#39;s Kellogg School of Management.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Have you ever been in a work situation where the boss made less than the employees?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> For instance, the chief scientific officer of a biotech company—whose research might be the crux of the business&#39;s success or failure—could be paid more than the CEO. George Yancopoulos, the chief scientific officer of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/REGN" class="">Regeneron Pharmaceuticals</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> has received almost $435 million in total compensation since 2012, according to securities filings, making him the company&#39;s highest-paid employee over that span. (Regeneron may be best known for its monoclonal antibody treatment for Covid.)</p><p> At some universities, the highest-paid employee isn&#39;t the president; it&#39;s the football coach or the person who manages the endowment. The $2.2 million pay package awarded to Yale University President Peter Salovey last fiscal year was one-third of what the chief investment officer earned, according to tax filings.</p><p> Leaders who successfully handle higher-paid employees find satisfaction in helping others shine, Taaffe says.</p><p> Warren Cereghino, a retired TV news director in California, says he kept pride at bay by reminding himself that viewers tuned in to watch his station&#39;s anchors, who earned more than he did as their boss. He says the on-air talent didn&#39;t abuse their sway.</p><p> Still, being privy to their contracts, he knew that some had negotiated a measure of editorial control in addition to large salaries. If there was a disagreement, he wouldn&#39;t necessarily win.</p><p> “Even though my name was on the door of the news director&#39;s office, there was a limit to my power,” he says.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Theo Francis contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Callum Borchers at <a href="mailto:callum.borchers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">callum.borchers@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/12865c40-068f-4100-aa18-f73fd5f66fae.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/higher-salary-workers-boss-manager-157cb4f4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/higher-salary-workers-boss-manager-157cb4f4<author><![CDATA[Callum Borchers]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>收购/合并/持股</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>美式足球</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>收购</category><category>合并</category><category>持股</category><category>企业行动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>美式足球</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Can Coinbase’s Blockchain Fix Its Losing Streak?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>加密货币交易所连续六个季度亏损，客户减少交易<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001120152"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831716?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">插图：Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/《华尔街日报》 </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001120152"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/vicky-ge-huang" itemprop="url" rel="author">Vicky Ge Huang</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 9 日下午 4:45（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-coinbases-blockchain-fix-its-losing-streak-cdc24a17"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/COIN" class="company-name">Coinbase Global</a>周三推出了一个供开发人员构建加密应用程序的平台，这是该<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/coinbase-posts-sixth-consecutive-quarterly-loss-2c506988?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">交易所为增加其核心交易业务之外的收入而采取的最新举措</a>。</p><p>该项目名为 Base，是一个区块链，在某些方面类似于手机上的 iOS 或 Android。它将为投资者提供一个汇款、在去中心化交易所进行交易、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/types/crypto?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">借贷加密货币</a>以及创建不可替代代币的平台。</p><p> Coinbase 首席财务官阿莱西亚·哈斯 (Alesia Haas) 表示，如果开发人员在网络上构建广受欢迎的应用程序，那么每次发生交易时，Coinbase 都会赚取费用。哈斯表示，Coinbase 可能需要数年时间才能从 Base 获得有意义的收入。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=995FCADF-1BFE-4730-BAF7-D522B47E6612&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcan-coinbases-blockchain-fix-its-losing-streak-cdc24a17&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美国证券交易委员会正在分别起诉币安和 Coinbase 两大加密货币平台。 《华尔街日报》的凯特琳·奥斯特罗夫对诉讼进行了详细分析。图片插图：Adam Adada/沉星培<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>该区块链是在 Coinbase 报告连续第六个季度亏损之后推出的。该交易所一直在与交易量下降作斗争，上季度活跃用户减少了 20%。 Coinbase 历来依赖于客户交易的费用。然而，Coinbase 的非交易收入历史上首次超过交易收入，标志着其商业模式的转变。</p><p> Base是所谓的以太坊第二层区块链，这意味着它是建立<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-news-today-09-15-2022/card/when-is-the-ethereum-merge--yfH2C1iAC5yfjIjdFZx8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在以太坊之上的</a>独立区块链，以提高交易成本和速度。</p><p> Base 接收大量交易，对它们进行批处理，然后压缩它们，然后将它们发布到以太坊。</p><p> “在以太坊上，每个人都开一辆车，这非常昂贵，因为每个人都必须为自己的汽车付费，”领导 Coinbase 区块链工作的 Jesse Pollak 说。 “有了 Base，我们就有了公共交通，所以现在一列火车就可以容纳数百人。”</p><p>根据<a href="https://dune.com/tk-research/base" target="_blank" class="icon none">Dune Analytics 的数据，</a>投资者在推出之前将价值超过 1.4 亿美元的加密货币从以太坊区块链发送到 Base，以便在新区块链上使用它们。</p><p>目前，Base 上有大约 20 个去中心化交易所可供使用，例如 Uniswap 以及借贷平台 Aave。</p><p> Coinbase 因 Base 的推出而面临声誉风险。它是一个公共且“无需许可”的区块链，这意味着任何人都可以匿名参与。甚至在正式推出之前，Base 就发现了一个涉及模因币的骗局。 BALD 代币是 7 月份在区块链上推出的笑话代币，在其开发商携投资者资金潜逃后，其价格跌至近乎于零。</p><p> Pollak 表示，Coinbase 将构建更多工具来帮助用户评估 Base 平台上产品的可信度，尽管这不会干扰区块链的“开放和无需许可”方面。</p><p>该公司还受到严格的监管审查。美国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sec-sues-coinbase-says-it-is-unregistered-broker-dealer-95ec0637?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">证券交易委员会于 6 月起诉 Coinbase</a> ，指控该公司违反了要求其注册为交易所并接受联邦机构监管的规定。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Base 能拯救 Coinbase 吗？为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>由于 Coinbase 在创建 Base 方面发挥着核心作用，理论上监管机构可以让该公司对区块链上的任何邪恶活动负责。</p>奥米德·马勒坎 (Omid Malekan)，哥伦比亚商学院兼职教授。<p></p><p> “想要提出这一论点的监管机构可以提出这一论点，”他说。 “但是，我确实认为，对于任何监管机构来说，这也是一种非常短视的处理这种情况的方式。”</p><p> Coinbase 更多地关注粘性收入来源，例如为希望推出持有比特币的交易所交易基金的资产管理公司提供托管服务。然而，SEC 多次拒绝这些 ETF 的申请。</p><p>投资者对资产管理公司对这些<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bitcoin-coinbase-are-soaring-despite-obstacles-facing-spot-bitcoin-etfs-d028ddab?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">比特币 ETF</a>的新申请的热情以及 Ripple 在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-earnings-07-14-2023/card/ripple-s-partial-win-in-sec-fight-could-lift-coinbase-stock-analysts-say-EwZdQDxg4WeKGZwpvBfZ?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与 SEC 的法律斗争</a>中取得部分胜利，最近几周提振了 Coinbase 的股价。该股今年已飙升 138%，但仍远低于 381 美元的首次发行价。</p><p>写信给 Vicky Ge Huang，邮箱： <a href="mailto:vicky.huang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">vicky.huang@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 20:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-coinbases-blockchain-fix-its-losing-streak-cdc24a17</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-coinbases-blockchain-fix-its-losing-streak-cdc24a17<author><![CDATA[Vicky Ge Huang]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>华尔街日报金融市场</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>证券/商品交易活动</category><category>区块链技术</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>加密货币交易所</category><category>金融服务</category><category>金融科技</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>技术</category><category>虚拟货币/加密货币</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Financial Performance</category><category> Earnings</category><category>新产品/服务</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Coinbase 全球</category><category>硬币</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>financial performance</category><category> earnings</category><category>新产品</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>证券</category><category>商品交换活动</category><category>区块链技术</category><category>银行业</category><category>信用</category><category>加密货币交易所</category><category>financial services</category><category>金融科技</category><category>投资</category><category>技术</category><category>虚拟货币</category><category>加密货币</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Special Counsel Got Search Warrant for Trump Twitter Account, Court Reveals]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这家社交媒体公司（现称为 X）因抗拒搜查令而被判藐视法庭罪，并被罚款 35 万美元<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122010"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="595" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832670?width=860&amp;height=595" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Special counsel Jack Smith obtained a search warrant that directed Twitter to produce records related to the @realDonaldTrump Twitter account.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：德鲁·安格勒/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122010"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">简· <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jan-wolfe" itemprop="url" rel="author">沃尔夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated Aug. 9, 2023 4:31 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/special-counsel-got-search-warrant-for-trump-twitter-account-court-reveals-ec6b4c83"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>华盛顿——根据一项新公布的法庭裁决，特别检察官杰克·史密斯今年早些时候获得了搜查令，要求 X（前身为 Twitter 的社交媒体公司）提供与唐纳德·特朗普 Twitter 帐户相关的数据和记录，该裁决维持了罚款。批评该公司对搜查令反应迟缓。</p><p> In a unanimous <a href="https://storage.courtlistener.com/recap/gov.uscourts.cadc.39513/gov.uscourts.cadc.39513.1208541751.0.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">3-0 decision</a> made public on Wednesday, the US Court of Appeals for the DC Circuit affirmed a lower-court decision that held the social-media company in contempt of court and imposed a $350,000 fine on it.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>法官弗洛伦斯·潘（Florence Pan）在法庭上写道：“地方法院在认定 Twitter 藐视法庭之前遵循了适当的程序，包括给 Twitter 一个表达意见的机会，以及一个消除其藐视法庭行为以避免制裁的机会。”</p><p>除了媒体电子邮件联系人的自动回复之外，X 没有立即回复评论请求。 Trump posted on his social-media website, Truth Social: “Just found out that Crooked Joe Biden&#39;s DOJ secretly attacked my Twitter account, making it a point not to let me know about this major &#39;hit&#39; on my civil rights.”</p><p> Smith is the special counsel appointed by Attorney General Merrick Garland to investigate Trump&#39;s effort to undo his election defeat, as well as his handling of classified documents. Smith has brought criminal charges against Trump in Florida and Washington, DC The former president has pleaded not guilty in both cases. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=CE44987D-1506-41EC-B44B-4F30D87D7BA0&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fspecial-counsel-got-search-warrant-for-trump-twitter-account-court-reveals-ec6b4c83&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Donald Trump&#39;s legal team said Monday that prosecutors&#39; request to prevent him from publicly sharing evidence in the federal Jan. 6 case violated his free-speech rights. Photo: Melissa Sue Gerrits/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>According to the DC Circuit decision, Smith&#39;s office in January applied for, and obtained, a search warrant that directed Twitter to produce data and records related to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trumps-2024-campaign-plans-collide-with-strategy-to-stay-out-of-jail-43c53342?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the @realDonaldTrump Twitter account</a> . The decision didn&#39;t say what kind of data and records the warrant sought.</p><p> The government also got a nondisclosure order that prohibited X from notifying anyone about the existence or contents of the warrant, including Trump. X challenged that order in court, saying the restrictions violated the company&#39;s First Amendment rights.</p><p> The clash began after billionaire <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">Elon Musk</a> completed his acquisition of the social-media company then known as Twitter. In early 2021, under its previous management, the platform suspended Trump permanently, citing the risk of incitement of violence after the Jan. 6 Capitol riot. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832672?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> X, the social-media company previously known as Twitter, is based in San Francisco.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: David Paul Morris/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Musk <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-says-twitter-would-reinstate-donald-trumps-account-after-online-poll-11668906083?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reinstated Trump&#39;s account</a> late last year, but the former president hasn&#39;t resumed posting on the platform.</p><p> US District Judge Beryl Howell</p> heard arguments in the case in February and sided with Smith&#39;s office. The argument was closed to the public.<p></p><p> X missed a deadline for complying with the warrant by three days, according to the court ruling. The Justice Department suggested sanctions that would accrue at a geometric rate: $50,000 a day, to double every day that Twitter didn&#39;t comply. Howell adopted that suggestion, saying that Twitter was sold for more than $40 billion and that Musk&#39;s net worth exceeded $180 billion at the time.</p><p> At the time, Howell was the chief judge for the federal district court in Washington. In that role, she heard challenges to subpoenas and other investigative steps taken by Smith&#39;s team of prosecutors, and routinely sided with the government.</p><p> <em>—Alexa Corse contributed to this article.</em></p><p>写信给简·沃尔夫 (Jan Wolfe)： <a href="mailto:jan.wolfe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jan.wolfe@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 20:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/special-counsel-got-search-warrant-for-trump-twitter-account-court-reveals-ec6b4c83</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/special-counsel-got-search-warrant-for-trump-twitter-account-court-reveals-ec6b4c83<author><![CDATA[Jan Wolfe]]></author><category>特朗普法律</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>公司变更</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>公司名称变更</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Social Media</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>特朗普法律</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>杰克·史密斯</category><category>Elon Musk</category><category>公司变更</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>企业名称变更</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>社交媒体</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item></channel></rss>